NARRATIVE:
DUI#: 23-54-036
Brian Lamar Taylor(DOB:11/28/1989)
Date/time of arrest: 03/03/2023 @0526hrs

CERTIFICATION AND TRAINING
*Trained in administering Standardized Field Sobriety Test through the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.

VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1)
        On March 3, 2023 at approximately 0510 hours, I, Tpr.Tenney (#7378) of the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack, was on patrol in the area of Still Meadows Blvd at Beaglin Park Drive in Salisbury, Maryland. At that time, I observed a maroon Chevrolet impala displaying Virgina Registration “TTF3527" facing  eastbound in the westbound lane of Still Meadows Blvd with its front driver’s side tire up over the curb. I positioned my patrol car, MSP marked unit E-47 westbound in front of the Impala and activated my emergency equipment. At that time, I observed the driver of the vehicle unconscious behind the wheel. I observed the Impala headlights and taillights aluminated. The engine of the vehicle was running, with exhaust coming from the tailpipe.
PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2)
I exited my vehicle wearing my full Maryland State Police issued Class-B uniform, complete with brass breast badge. I approached the Impala and began to tap on the window to wake the driver. After several attempts to wake the driver with no response, I opened the Impala’s front driver's side door and attempted to wake the driver up. The driver of the vehicle regained consciousness approximately two times briefly before falling back to sleep. I then reached into the Impala and turned the vehicle off. On the third attempt the driver regained consciousness and began speaking with me. At that time, I observed the driver’s eyes to be glassy and I detected a moderate odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from inside the vehicle. I then asked the driver what happened. He stated that he had a long night and he was staying here. I then asked the driver why he was facing the wrong direction and up on the curb. The driver stated that it was the last spot available. I asked if the driver needed medical attention. The driver then replied no. At that time, I located an open 24 ounce can of Natty Daddy located on the passenger's side floorboard.   The driver then provided me with his Virginia driver’s license which identified him as Brian Lamar Taylor (DOB:11/28/1989). The photo on his Virginia driver's licenses matched the driver's appearance. I then asked Taylor if he had consumed any alcohol prior to driving. Taylor stated that he consumed two 16 once Coors lights approximately two hours ago in Pocomoke, Maryland. I then stated my name, rank, badge number, and informed him that he was being audibly and visually recorded. Taylor stated ok.
PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)
  Do you have any medical conditions? Taylor answered "No".
        Do you have any pre-existing injuries? Taylor stated “No"
        Do you take any medications? Taylor stated “no”

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (6/6 clues observed)
        The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus (HGN) Test. The tip of my pen was used as the test's stimulus and held approximately 12 inches from Taylor's eyes. Taylor was instructed to keep his head still while following and focusing on the tip of the stimulus with his eyes until told to stop. Taylor’s pupils appeared to be equal in size and showed equal tracking. I asked Taylor if he understood the directions and he stated yes. The results were as follows:
  1. Lack of smooth pursuit in both eyes.
  2. Distinct and sustained Nystagmus at maximum deviation in both eyes.
  3. Onset of Nystagmus prior to 45 degrees in both eyes.
Vertical Gaze Nystagmus was observed.

WALK AND TURN (3/8 clues observed)

        Prior to Taylor performing the test, I explained and demonstrated how the test should be performed. Taylor was instructed to place his left foot on an imaginary straight line and place his right foot on the same line in front of his left foot with the heel of his right foot touching the toes of his left foot. Taylor was to place his hands flat at his sides and to remain in his position until he was told to begin. Taylor was instructed to take nine (9) steps on the straight-line touching heel to toe on each step. Taylor was told to keep his hands flat at his sides, keep his eyes focused on his feet, and to count every step out loud. After completing his ninth step Taylor was demonstrated and explained to keep his lead foot on the line, and to take a series of small steps around his lead foot with his rear foot to turn completely around.  Taylor was then explained and demonstrated to take nine more heel to toe steps on the same line in the opposite direction of the first nine steps. The second nine steps were to be performed identical to the first nine steps. Taylor was instructed that once he began the test he was not to stop walking until the test was complete. Taylor was again instructed to keep his hands down at his sides, look down at his feet, and count each step out loud. After explaining and demonstrating the test, I asked Taylor if he completely understood the instructions and she stated "Yes". The results were as follows:
        Instruction stage:
1.            Cannot keep balance/ breaks feet apart. Taylor broke his feet from the starting position on three occasion.
        Walking Stage (first nine):
1. Raised arms for balance on steps: 1
         The turn:
                Completed unsatisfactory. Taylor did keep his lead foot planted while completing the turn and used his momentum to swing his body around without taking any steps with his rear foot.
        Walking Stage (second nine):
No clue was observed.

ONE LEG STAND (2/4 clues observed)
Prior to Taylor performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be performed.Taylor was instructed to stand with his heels together and hands down by his sides while the instructions were given. Taylor was instructed not to begin the test until told to do so and after it had been demonstrated. When instructed to start he was to keep his hands down by his sides, and raise the foot of his choice off the ground approximately 6 inches. While his foot was raised he was to keep his leg straight, watch his raised foot, and to count out loud by and to continue the test until told to stop. Taylor was asked if he understood the test and the instructions to which he stated yes. The results were as follows:
  1. Sways right to left on :06, and :11
  2. Uses arms for balance on  :06, and :11

PRELIMIINARY BREATH TEST
Preliminary breath test offered and refused.
 
ARREST
 
                Based on the following, I had reason to believe that Taylor was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol: 

                * Observations while the driver was operating the vehicle 

                * Observation during personal contact while speaking with the driver  

        I advised Taylor that he was under arrest for driving under the influence of Alcohol. Taylor was transported to the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack for processing. A search incident to arrest was conducted and revealed no contraband was on his person, and nothing was in his mouth. Nothing was introduced to his mouth while he was in my custody. Taylor was read the DR-15 at 0604 hours and refused the intoximeter. 

All events occurred in Wicomico County Maryland.
 Case closed by arrest.
